From your code to distributed work.

When you write a chain like filter, then group-by, then count, here is what happens behind the scenes.

The driver builds a logical plan from your dataframe chain. The Catalyst optimizer rewrites it — pushing filters down, reordering joins, dropping unused columns. The plan becomes a physical plan, then a directed acyclic graph of stages. Each stage splits into tasks — one task per partition. Tasks ship to executors and run in parallel across their see-pee-you cores.

Three vocabulary words to lock in now, because they show up on the exam.

A job is what one action triggers. One count call equals one job.

A stage is a slice of work between shuffles. A new shuffle starts a new stage.

A task is the smallest unit of work. One partition, processed by one executor core.
